    <name>
      <text>Application of reciprocals - period of a pendulum</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>The <strong>period</strong> (\(T\)) of a swinging pendulum is the reciprocal of its <strong>frequency</strong> (\(f\)). The relationship is given by the formula:</p>
\(T = \frac{1}{f} \)

<p>This means: if you know the frequency, you can find the period by taking <strong>1 divided by the frequency</strong>.</p><p>A digital sensor measures a pendulum's frequency as <strong>{@freq_disp@} swings per second (Hz)</strong>.</p>
<p>Use the <strong>table of reciprocals</strong> provided to calculate the pendulum's period in seconds.</p>
<p>Period (\(T\)) \(=\) [[input:ans1]] s [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>We are asked to find the period of a pendulum. The period <strong>T</strong> is the reciprocal of the frequency:</p>

\[ T = \frac{1}{{@freq_disp@}} \]

<p>We use a mathematical table of reciprocals to find this value:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Locate the row corresponding to <strong>{@float(part_a)@}</strong> in the column labelled \(x\).</li>
  <li>Move across to the main column headed <strong>{@part_b@}</strong>. The value at this intersection is <strong>{@table_val_main@}</strong>.</li>
  <li>Continue along the same row to the "SUBTRACT" (Mean Difference) column headed <strong>{@part_c@}</strong>. The value here corresponds to <strong>{@sub_num@}</strong>, representing 0.000{@sub_num@}.</li>
  <li>Subtract the mean difference from the main table value.  
      (We subtract because the reciprocal function \(y = 1/x\) decreases as \(x\) increases.)</li>
</ol>

<p>Calculation:</p>
\[ {@table_val_main@} - 0.000{@sub_num@} = {@ta@} \]

<p>Thus, the period of the pendulum is <strong>{@ta@} seconds</strong>.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
